<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Stall Car Event Point
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        Forces a referenced Create Vehicle Event Point into a stalled state when mission logic triggers it.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        What Stall Car Event Points Do
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        A <Bold>Stall Car</Bold> Event Point targets an existing <Bold>Create Vehicle</Bold> Event
        Point and applies a stall action to that vehicle. It is used when a mission wants a vehicle
        to stop working, become unusable, or be removed from active driving as part of scripted
        logic.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Stall Car is not the same as Lock Vehicle. Lock Vehicle changes whether a vehicle can be
        entered. Stall Car represents the vehicle failing or stopping as a mission event, often after
        a waypoint, chase step, or other scripted condition.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Practical meaning:</Run>
                <Run> Use Stall Car when a specific vehicle should break down, stop, or become disabled after a mission condition.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Common Properties
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Stall Car uses the standard Event Point common properties: index number, Event Point type,
        letter group, colour, position, facing direction, trigger settings, and listening mode.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The index number and Event Point type are automatic. Colour and letter group should usually
        match the vehicle, chase, crash, escape, or objective chain that causes the stall.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Position
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The Stall Car Event Point's own position is usually not the vehicle position. The vehicle is
        selected by the <Bold>Vehicle</Bold> field. Use this point's position for organising the
        event chain unless the trigger itself is spatial.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Trigger Settings
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Trigger settings decide when the vehicle stalls. Existing missions use <Bold>Dependency</Bold>
        with <Bold>Active</Bold>, where another Event Point such as a Simple Waypoint or Kill
        Waypoint causes the stall.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Stall Car-Specific Settings
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Stall Car has one type-specific setting. <Bold>Data[0]</Bold> stores the vehicle Event Point
        index.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Vehicle</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Vehicle is the Event Point index of the <Bold>Create Vehicle</Bold> entry that should be
        stalled. The editor stores this value in the range <Bold>1-2048</Bold>. It should point at
        the vehicle itself, not the waypoint, enemy, message, or trigger that causes the stall.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2" CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Important:</Run>
                <Run> Vehicle is the Create Vehicle Event Point being stalled. EP Ref belongs to the trigger condition and is usually a different Event Point.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        How Missions Trigger Stall Car
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Existing Stall Car usage is focused on scripted mission state changes. Useful trigger
        patterns are:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Dependency</Bold> - stalls the vehicle after another Event Point fires.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Active</Bold> - the observed listening mode for Stall Car entries.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Authoring tip:</Run>
                <Run> Create the vehicle first, note its Event Point index, then trigger Stall Car from the mission condition that should disable it.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Common Stall Car Patterns
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Stall After A Waypoint</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Dependency</Bold> on a Simple Waypoint when a vehicle should stall after a route,
        chase, or scripted movement step reaches a particular point.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>carbomb1.ucm</Bold>, Stall Car <Bold>285</Bold> stalls Vehicle Event Point
        <Bold>82</Bold>. It uses <Bold>Dependency</Bold> on Event Point <Bold>92</Bold>, a
        <Bold>Simple Waypoint</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">How to author it</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Set <Bold>Vehicle</Bold> to the Create Vehicle Event Point that should stall. Set
        <Bold>Triggered By</Bold> to <Bold>Dependency</Bold> and set <Bold>EP Ref</Bold> to the
        waypoint or mission step that should cause the stall.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Stall After A Kill Waypoint</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use a dependency on a Kill Waypoint when the vehicle should stall after a related waypoint or
        route target has been removed.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>carbomb1.ucm</Bold>, Stall Car <Bold>286</Bold> stalls Vehicle Event Point
        <Bold>6</Bold>. It uses <Bold>Dependency</Bold> on Event Point <Bold>8</Bold>, a
        <Bold>Kill Waypoint</Bold> that kills Event Point <Bold>5</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Disable A Player-Drivable Vehicle</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Stall Car can target vehicles that are otherwise player-drivable. This is useful when a
        mission needs to stop an escape route, force a transition, or make a chase vehicle fail at a
        scripted moment.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>police1.ucm</Bold>, Stall Car <Bold>164</Bold> stalls Vehicle Event Point
        <Bold>71</Bold>, a <Bold>Taxi</Bold> with <Bold>Player Drives</Bold> behaviour. It is
        triggered by <Bold>Dependency</Bold> on Event Point <Bold>90</Bold>, a Simple Waypoint.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Driving Test Or Route Fail State</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Stall Car can also be used in driving-focused missions when a route or test condition should
        stop the active vehicle.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>testdrive1a.ucm</Bold>, Stall Car <Bold>70</Bold> stalls Vehicle Event Point
        <Bold>2</Bold>, a <Bold>Police Sedan</Bold>. It is triggered by <Bold>Dependency</Bold> on
        Event Point <Bold>167</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Basic Stall Car Workflow
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Create or identify the <Bold>Create Vehicle</Bold> Event Point to stall.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Add a <Bold>Stall Car</Bold> Event Point.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set <Bold>Vehicle</Bold> to the Create Vehicle Event Point index.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set the trigger, usually <Bold>Dependency</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set <Bold>EP Ref</Bold> to the Event Point that should cause the stall.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Use <Bold>Active</Bold> for the listening mode.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Test the vehicle before and after the trigger to confirm it stalls at the intended mission moment.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Keep related vehicle logic grouped by colour and letter for easier debugging.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2" CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Final checklist:</Run>
                <Run> Vehicle points at the intended Create Vehicle Event Point, EP Ref points at the trigger condition, and the vehicle stalls only at the correct mission moment.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

</FlowDocument>
